nt|I have heard some reasonable players make the assertion that "vulnerability is for children". That is completely absurd in my view. The vulnerability affects the scoring, which influences the expected outcomes of various bridge actions. In my view, being able to "play the vulnerability well" is a much underappreciated part of what it takes to win at bridge.|
pg| ***** 6 ***** |


nt|When nobody is vulnerable, making an aggressive competitive bid is more dangerous than most players realize. If you get caught and go for a number it is almost always bad as the opponents'  300-point non-vulnerable game bonus is not worth that much. |
pg| ***** 7 ***** |


nt|If it is your game bonus that is in question, it does not pay to stretch when you are not vulnerable (as the swing you gain when game makes is worth about the same as what you lose if game goes down). When you are vulnerable it is different as the 500-point game bonus makes it right to stretch to game contracts that are somewhat against the odds to make.|
pg| ***** 8 ***** |


nt|In my view, ^*BJeff Meckstroth^*N and ^*BEric Rodwell^*N understand the vulnerability better than anyone. I have learned a great deal about this aspect of the game by studying their moves. When nobody is vulnerable Jeff calls it, "the burn vulnerability". I think that sums it up very well - when you play with fire and nobody is vulnerable it is easy to get burned!|
